did.abstract: The Women's Philharmonic was a professional orchestra dedicated to the promotion of women composers and performers. The collections contains files related to all aspects of the organization including programs, business records, music library materials, correspondence, and more.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Women's Philharmonic collection consists of mixed materials reflecting this organization's administrative and artistic lifespan which ranged from 1981 to 2004. A brief overview of this collection's contents includes: programs; photographs; biographical materials of composers, conductors and guest artists; orchestra personnel rosters; financial and grant records; fund raising activities; audience surveys and marketing efforts; concert production notes; correspondence which ranges from office memoranda to letters from Nan Washburn, Elizabeth Min, Miriam Abrams, JoAnn Falletta, Apo Hsu and others ; music library materials and catalogs; female composer and conductor initiative materials such as the National Women's Composer Resource Center as well as press and reviews collected during its twenty-four year history.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Funded in part by the Women's Studies Department at Stanford University.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: [identification of item], Women's Philharmonic records (M1470). Dept. of Special Collections and University Archives, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, Calif.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Collection is open for research use. Audio-visual materials are not available in original format, and must be reformatted to a digital use copy.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: All requests to reproduce, publish, quote from, or otherwise use collection materials must be submitted in writing to the Head of Special Collections and University Archives, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, California 94305-6064. Consent is given on behalf of Special Collections as the owner of the physical items and is not intended to include or imply permission from the copyright owner. Such permission must be obtained from the copyright owner, heir(s) or assigns. See: http://library.stanford.edu/spc/using-collections/permission-publish. Restrictions also apply to digital representations of the original materials. Use of digital files is restricted to research and educational purposes.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Gift of the Women's Philharmonic, 2005, accessions 2005-122 and 2005-209. Additional material transferred from the Music Library, 2007, accession 2007-020.

scopecontent.head: Administration
scopecontent.p: This includes all materials relating to the office and its organization; job descriptions; website design; and correspondence relating to everyday tasks as well as from patrons; local arts organizations with whom the Women's Philharmonic may have had relationships with; legal counsel materials and miscellaneous in-office correspondences. Also included are merchandise materials and office materials.

scopecontent.head: Legal
scopecontent.p: This file contains legal support materials; copyright advice, artist contract samples and correspondence regarding a potential lawsuit concerning the Women's Philharmonic practice of hiring only of female musicians for the orchestra.

scopecontent.head: Catalog
scopecontent.p: This contains a list of female composers which was researched and developed by the Women's Philharmonic music librarian. One catalogue represents women composers from the Baroque era to the 1990s; a second catalogue pairs publishers with various female composers to aid with the acquisition of repertoire. Other catalogs included are an International catalog and a Black Women composers catalog.

scopecontent.head: Grants and Foundations
scopecontent.p: This series contains grants, corporate sponsorships, and donor foundations through which the Women's Philharmonic sought funding. Some of the grants included are the National Endowment for the Arts (NEA); Cultural Equity Grant (CEG); Grants for the Arts (GFTA); the San Francisco Arts Commission (SFAC) and Meet the Composer. Corporate sponsor inquires and correspondences are also included as are foundation awards and correspondences. Audit materials and box office materials (invoices, receipts, tickets sold, etc.) are also included.

scopecontent.head: Inaugural season
scopecontent.p: This includes correspondences of Elizabeth Seja Min, Nan Washburn and Miriam Abrams, the founders of the Women's Philharmonic. The majority of the material is from the early 1980s and represents the organization's first ten years. This series includes audtion calls for various orchestral instruments; letters of inquiry from conductors, musicians and guest artists; musician union negotiations and correspondence from musicans; office memos and other correspondences relating to the organizing and development of an orchestra, its repertoire and its concerts. Additional information relating to the Community Women's Orchestra, an amateur orchestra organized by the Women's Philharmonic and conducted by Nan Washburn is also included. These include: program notes; audition announcements; orchestra member surveys and correspondence.
